Triggers (Automated database events)

	- A Trigger is a set of SQL statements that automatically executes (fires) when a specific event occurs on a table.

		These events can be:

			- INSERT

			- UPDATE

			- DELETE

	Simple Definition: A trigger is a database object that automatically executes a set of SQL statements when a specified event occurs on a table.

	=> Types of Triggers

		Triggers are classified based on timing:

		1. BEFORE Trigger

			Executes before the event happens.

		2. AFTER Trigger

			Executes after the event happens.

	=> Example Table: employees

		| id | name | salary |
		| -- | ---- | ------ |
		| 1  | Ravi | 50000  |

	=> Example 1: BEFORE INSERT Trigger

		- Automatically set created_at before inserting a record.

			DELIMITER $$

			CREATE TRIGGER before_insert_employee
			BEFORE INSERT ON employees
			FOR EACH ROW
			BEGIN
			   SET NEW.created_at = NOW();
			END $$

			DELIMITER ;

	=> Example 2: AFTER INSERT Trigger

		- Log data after inserting a record.

			DELIMITER $$

			CREATE TRIGGER after_insert_employee
			AFTER INSERT ON employees
			FOR EACH ROW
			BEGIN
			   INSERT INTO logs(message)
			   VALUES (CONCAT('New employee added: ', NEW.name));
			END $$

			DELIMITER ;

	=> Example 3: BEFORE UPDATE Trigger

		- Prevent negative salary.

			DELIMITER $$

			CREATE TRIGGER before_update_salary
			BEFORE UPDATE ON employees
			FOR EACH ROW
			BEGIN
			   IF NEW.salary < 0 THEN
			      SET NEW.salary = 0;
			   END IF;
			END $$

			DELIMITER ;

	Example 4: AFTER DELETE Trigger

		- Log deleted records.

			DELIMITER $$

			CREATE TRIGGER after_delete_employee
			AFTER DELETE ON employees
			FOR EACH ROW
			BEGIN
			   INSERT INTO logs(message)
			   VALUES (CONCAT('Deleted employee: ', OLD.name));
			END $$

			DELIMITER ;

	=> OLD vs NEW Keywords

		| Keyword | Description               |
		| ------- | ------------------------- |
		| NEW     | New value (INSERT/UPDATE) |
		| OLD     | Old value (UPDATE/DELETE) |

	Example:

		NEW.salary → new salary value

		OLD.salary → previous salary value

	=> When Triggers Are Fired

		INSERT → BEFORE INSERT → INSERT → AFTER INSERT
		UPDATE → BEFORE UPDATE → UPDATE → AFTER UPDATE
		DELETE → BEFORE DELETE → DELETE → AFTER DELETE

	=> Advantages of Triggers

		- Automates tasks

		- Ensures data integrity

		- Maintains audit logs

		- Enforces business rules

	=> Disadvantages of Triggers

		- Hard to debug

		- Hidden logic (not visible in queries)

		- Can affect performance

	=> Real Project Example

		In a banking system:

			- Trigger logs every transaction automatically

			- Prevents invalid updates

		In an E-commerce system:

			- Automatically updates stock after order

			- Logs order history

	=> Best Interview Answer (Short)

		- A trigger is a database object that automatically executes a set of SQL statements in response to events like INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE on a table.